3.1.8 Approximability of Orthogonal Polynomials

We now brieﬂy review some general polynomial approximation results. One can ﬁnd their proofs from standard books on approximation theory (see, for instance, Timan (1994), Cheney (1998)).
The ﬁrst fundamental result is the remarkable Weierstrass Theorem, which states that any continuous function in a ﬁnite interval can be uniformly approximated by an algebraic polynomial.
Theorem 3.13. Let (a, b) be a ﬁnite interval. Then for any u ∈ C[a, b], and any ε > 0, there exist n ∈ N and pn ∈ Pn such that

